		<!-- page code -->			
		<h1 class="accountants">Capital<br />Gains Rules</h1>
		<p>The Jobs and Growth Tax Relief Reconciliation Act of 2003 made significant changes to the way long-term capital gains are taxed. Prior to enactment of the new law, long-term capital gains were taxed at a maximum rate of 20% (10% for taxpayers in the 10% &amp; 15% tax brackets). The new reduced tax rates for long-term capital gains are effective for sales on or after May 6, 2003.</p>
		<p>In A Nutshell, here are the rules for long-term capital gains on the sale of investment real estate effective May 6, 2003 -</p>
        <table border="0">
			<tbody><tr>
				<td>Maximum Tax Rate</td>
				<td>Long-Term Capital Gains (property held more than 12 months)</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>

				<td>15%</td>
				<td>Taxpayers in a regular tax bracket higher than 15%.</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td>5%</td>
				<td>Taxpayers in the 15% or 10% regular tax bracket.</td>
			</tr>

			<tr>
				<td>0%</td>
				<td>Taxpayers in the 15% or 10% regular tax brackets commencing in year 2008.</td>
			</tr>
		</tbody></table>
		<p>Depreciation Taken On Real Estate Investments remains taxable at a 25% tax rate (15% for taxpayers in 10% and 15% tax bracket). The remainder of the gain from the sale of depreciable real property is taxed at the 15%/5% maximum tax rates referred to above. This rule is unchanged by the new tax act.</p>
		<!-- end page code -->

